<DOC><DOCNO> AP880223-0129 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-88 1258EST</FILEID><FIRST>r p AM-SouthDakotaAt-A-Glance     02-23 0357</FIRST><SECOND>AM-South Dakota At-A-Glance,350</SECOND><HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp, Bjt</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Here, at a glance, are the methods for pickingdelegates from South Dakota to attend the 1988 Democratic andRepublican national conventions this summer.</TEXT><HEAD>DEMOCRATS</HEAD><TEXT>   Method: Caucus   Date: Saturday, March 12   Presidential filing deadline: Tuesday, December 29, 1987   Non-binding presidential primary: Tuesday, February 23   Candidates filed: Bruce Babbitt, Michael Dukakis, RichardGephardt, Albert Gore, Gary Hart, Jesse Jackson, Paul Simon   Pledged delegates: 15   Super delegates: 4   Total delegates: 19   Delegates allocated: Saturday, March 12   Selection of delegates: Saturday, March 12 and Saturday, April 23   South Dakota Democrats choose pledged national conventiondelegates through a one-tiered caucus system put in place after thenational party determined the state's presidential primary wasbeing held in violation of the rules.   The primary on Feb. 23 will be a non-binding ``beauty contest,''although state party officials said they would feel bound by honor_ if not by rules _ to honor the wishes of the voters in awardingnational convention delegates to presidential candidates.   South Dakota, which has just one congressional district, willchoose 10 congressional-district delegates at a statewide caucus tobe held in Mitchell on March 12. The party has been compelled toprovide bus transportation to any Democrat needing a ride to thecaucus.   The state's remaining five pledged national convention delegateswill be picked by the state committee on April 23 and will beallocated among presidential candidates in proportion to theresults of March 12 caucus.</TEXT><HEAD>REPUBLICANS</HEAD><TEXT>   Method: Primary   Date: Tuesday, February 23   Presidential filing deadline: Tuesday, December 29, 1987   Candidates filed: George Bush, Bob Dole, Jack Kemp, PatRobertson, Pete du Pont, Alexander Haig   Delegates: 18   Delegates allocated: Tuesday, February 23   Selection of delegates: Tuesday, February 23   All of South Dakota's 18 delegates to the Republican NationalConvention will be elected directly from the primary ballot. Sincethe state has one congressional district, all delegates will beelected at-large.   Delegates will be awarded to presidential candidates inproportion to the results of the primary. A candidate must receiveat least 20 percent of the vote to qualify for any delegates.</TEXT></DOC>